The print shop is finally back (with some new work too!) It was a goal of mine for 2023 to get back in the studio, so that means making everywhere that I go an absolute mess since I’m currently studio-less. ⁣
⁣
The last time I finished a full series was seven years ago (crazy), with 2016’s Close To You. As soon as that wrapped, I started working on a very large-scale mixed media series, Women, that I never finished. I’ve thought about it a lot since and decided that now’s the time. ⁣
⁣
I’m way too low on bandwidth right now to write a coherent statement on it, but each work is approximately 5 x 7 feet and contains carefully hidden details of a specific woman’s life that I hope start conversations about their story as well as our place in society at large. More to come. ⁣
⁣
For now, I’ve posted the first completed piece from that series, Scarlet, in the shop. It’s available as a limited edition 12 x 16 inch signed giclée print. ⁣
⁣
As always, all prints are available framed or unframed. If you want a custom size, mat, or frame, shoot an email or DM me and I’ll see what we can do 🤍
⁣

⚡️ Nerdy niche collector moment ⚡️
⁣
A couple of years ago, I saw a sponsored ad for a Voluptuous Horror of Karen Black used pick (Samoa’s!) at auction. “That’s really fucking cool,” I thought. And so, as any good Capricorn does, I placed a bid and feverishly continued to up the ante until I won. ⁣
⁣
As someone who is both a guitarist and a collector, it kind of surprised me that I never thought about starting a stage-used pick collection. And now here we are two years later, knee deep in… picks. To be expected. ⁣
⁣
My latest is the first custom pick of Johnny Ramone’s from 1974, one that means a lot to me, but they’re all so special. Here are a few of my favorites 🎸🤍⁣
⁣
Nikki Sixx, Motley Crue, 1987 / Mick Mars, Motley Crue, 1989 / Twiggy and Marilyn Manson, Manson’s Mechanical Animals tour, 1998 / Johnny Ramone, The Ramones, 1974 / Tony Iommi, Black Sabbath, 1989 / Samoa, The Voluptuous Horror of Karen Black, 2015 / Joan Jett, 1985 / Slash, Velvet Revolver, 2004 / Lita Ford, first solo pick post-Runaways, 1982 / Sylvain Sylvain (🤍), New York Dolls, 2009
Cringing and pressing “post.” Finally an update. Thank you 🤍

I’ve always been an accidental collector of things. When I was a kid I went to a store with $5 one day and the only thing I could afford there was a pack of basketball cards. I bought it, pulled a piece of game used jersey, and fell in love. Five years later, I owned and traded over 100,000. ⁣
⁣
As I got older, the objects of my collections changed a bit (these days it’s mostly guitars and stage used guitar picks), but I always knew that I wanted to own a possession from each of my heroes, one being Janis Joplin. But, as my life can never be that simple, I decided that each object I acquired would have to represent them in some way, almost in a sense to protect and physically immortalize their legacy. ⁣
⁣
I wasn’t sure it would ever happen with Janis since we lost her so young and so long ago, but I’ve been desperately eyeing auctions for years and finally found something that I loved a few weeks ago. After days of bidding, I won it, and it finally arrived today. ⁣
⁣
This Italian bag was Janis’s and she gifted it to a venue employee after they complimented her on it before a show. It had been in the collection of Irwin Pate’s for years until he died in 2018 at the age of 87. I was so struck by the story and decided instantly that this object did, in fact, cement her legacy – her kindness and humility were legendary. ⁣
⁣
The coolest there ever was 🤍

Found an old archive of Prim tonight on one of my hard drives. It’s so strange to look back now – at the age of 29 – at an edition that I published when I was 16. I truly didn’t think that I was doing anything remarkable at the time and I quite honestly never understood the media storm around it. In my head, both then and now, nothing is impossible, so why couldn’t a 16-year-old become an international print fashion magazine editor? ⁣
⁣
Being initially successful during an era of hard copy print and early (well, earlier) internet is incredibly bizarre because the once-endless traces of most of it have been lost to time, leaving nothing but memories (for those who were there) and lore (for the ones who were not). ⁣
⁣
Each edition was over 300 pages and we worked with more than 6,000 contributors throughout the years. We were extremely ahead of our time. And I don’t say that because of *me*, I say that due to the brilliant, remarkable, brave, and genius creatives that helped us become what we were.
⁣
I’ve been thinking of making a digital archive of our editions for a while now just to have all of their work live on endlessly. It’s my intention to get around to it soon. ⁣
⁣
Progression forever x

Today, The Provocateur is finally reborn as Noir. ⁣
⁣
My first (very accidental) love was media, and Noir acts as a passionate love letter to a mediascape that I so terribly miss. ⁣
⁣
We will have no ads, no clickbait, no influencers, no celebrity news – nothing that does not matter. ⁣
⁣
But what we will have is content that is stimulating. Content that makes you think, reflect, admire, and inspire. ⁣
⁣
Oh, and since Provocateur merged with Lenoir to form Noir, we’re a brand too, so we’re going to have non-RTW product drops soon (like within-the-next-year soon!) ⁣
⁣
Noir will be a crossover between a modern-day media outlet and a blog. It is my hope to create a community – similar to the once-booming blogosphere – where women can come to our site and know exactly what to expect. Not fifty articles being overwhelmingly and mindlessly churned out a day, but very thoughtful, deliberate pieces that will engage you and enrich you. Content that you actually have the time to consume – not just haphazard fuel to a hopeful ad revenue fire.⁣
⁣
Media isn’t failing, 𝘰𝘶𝘵𝘭𝘦𝘵𝘴 are failing. I don’t think that many today are doing it correctly – even those that I used to admire the most – and that is why the landscape is crashing. ⁣
⁣
Luckily, I’ve never been afraid to do things a little (or a lot) differently. ⁣
⁣
Happy to be here. Happy to do this again. I’ve had so much fun getting it here and I’m even more excited for what’s to come. ⁣
⁣
Love you all and hope that you love it, too. ⁣
⁣
x, K

For Noir’s launch, I spoke with one of my favorites, the one and only @ditavonteese, about transformation, self-confidence, Dietrich, breakups, and her new Las Vegas revue.⁣
⁣
“People will always have a dislike for women who are harnessing their sexual power and using it in a different way than they've seen before. Because, you know, it's one thing to have a sex tape and apologize for it, but it's another thing to create these stripscapes on stage and to be deliberately flaunting your body – that can make some people angry. And in the same way, it can empower and inspire other people too. So one of the things that I've always loved about what I do is like, ‘Wow, isn't it interesting how one thing can make someone feel empowered, but the same thing can make people feel offended, degraded, or angry?’ But it's just a reminder that there's different strokes for different folks. Someone will take it one way and another person will take it a totally different way. I've always just stuck to my path and done my best to keep my blinders on and keep doing what I do.”⁣
⁣
